Introduction¶

This data set contains 13 attributes that are used as predictors for heart attacks in patients. Some of these attributes are age, sex, chest pain, resting blood pressure, cholestoral, and some others. The target column uses binary classification to see if someone is at risk for heart disease. 0=no risk, 1=more risk to a heart attack.

I am going to use k-means clustering as an unsupervised learning model method to identify the at risk groups. I am also going to be using a few supervised learning methods such as k-nearest neighbors and logistic regression to make predictions on if patients have an increase risk of a heart attack or not.

I will then compare the unsupervised and supervised models together to determine which has performed better and if there are any limitations with either of the models.

I will also do some exploratory data analysis to see if I visually find any patterns in the data that can provide some information on the risk factors to heart attacks.

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC, n.d.), in the United States, heart disease is the leading cause of death for both men and women. Heart Disease accounts for every 1 and 5 deaths. It is important to look at the factors that put individuals at risk for heart disease so that we can work to prevent these risk factors.

In [55]:
# Create correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = heart.corr()

# Create a larger figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))

# Create heatmap
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, fmt=".2f", cmap="RdBu", ax=ax)

# Set title and display the heatmap
plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Features")
plt.show()

Only two features show correlation with each other above 0.5 in the positive or negative direction. This is the feature "oldpeak" which is ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest and "slope" which is the slop of the peak exercise ST segment. This makes sense on how these features would show some correlation because they are both measuring ST segment which is from electrocardiogram data measuring the electrical signals from the heart and someone's heart beat.

Since the correlation is still only at -0.58 I do not think I need to adjust this data set to prevent colliniarity. I do not think colliniarity will affect my modeling based on this correlation matrix.

Supervised Learning, Logistic Regression and K-Nearest Neighbors¶

The data is already split into training and test sets. I am going to perform logistic regression which is a good method for binary class classification and also k-nearest neighbors.

I am going to perform a cross-validation to see what hyperparameters perform best for K-Nearest Neighbors

Logistic Regression¶

K-Nearest Neighbors¶

In [86]:
# creating a cross-validation for hyperparameters 
# CV 
knn=KNeighborsClassifier()
# creating hyperparameters grid 
param_grid = {'n_neighbors': [2, 3, 5, 7], # Different values for k
             'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'], # Weighting scheme for neighbors  
             'p': [1, 2] # distance metric (1: Manhattan, 2: Euclidean)
             }

# grid-search 
grid_search=GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, cv=5)

grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# best number of clusters 
best = grid_search.best_params_

print(best)

{'n_neighbors': 7, 'p': 1, 'weights': 'distance'}

y_pred_knn = knn.predict(X_test)

Conclusion¶

Summary of Results Overall, the Logistic Regression model performed a lot better than the k-means clustering model with 2 clusters and with 5 cluster and also performed better than the k-nearest neighbors model in all measures. Supervised learning performed better than unsupervised learning for this dataset. This could be because there is binary classification of a yes or no, increased risk of heart attack or no increased risk of heart attack. It seems like unsupervised learning models, especially k-means clustering is limited with this type of classification.

A logistic regression model performs well and lets us know that it will be able to predict risk of a heart attack based on the 13 attributes at a high accuracy of 88.5%. Based on the correlation heatmap, chest pain is the most correlated with the target value of predicting a heart attack. This makes sense because most people experience pain in their chest while they are currently having a heart attack.

This project could look at other unsupervised models for further investigation. I do not think a different supervised model would perform better than logistic regression because it performed decently well. Unsupervised modeling may just not work well with this data set, it didn't need PCA for dimensionality reduction which is a main task for unsupervised learning. There are probably other data sets that perform better with k-means clustering methods, probably data sets that do not have binary classification but a few different groups of similar data points with similar attributes.
